<span id="freeTextContainer5507258222505137195">Based on a true story, this beautifully written little book is a testament to the struggle for intellectual freedom.<br/>Written in a very descriptive , and living way, it tells of the story of two 17 year old boys in Mao&apos;s China who are among the millions of Chinese youth, forced to undergo &apos;Re-education&apos; , a type of deathlike existance in China&apos;s re-education camps , carrying excrement up and down a mountain.<br/><br/>Their life is given meaning by their meeting up with a pretty , young seamstress , and the </span>
  <span id="freeText5507258222505137195" style="display:none">Based on a true story, this beautifully written little book is a testament to the struggle for intellectual freedom.<br />Written in a very descriptive , and living way, it tells of the story of two 17 year old boys in Mao's China who are among the millions of Chinese youth, forced to undergo 'Re-education' , a type of deathlike existance in China's re-education camps , carrying excrement up and down a mountain.<br /><br />Their life is given meaning by their meeting up with a pretty , young seamstress , and the discovery of a book full of 19th century novels, in the intellectually stifling climate of Mao's China , where all litereature , other than Communist propaganda, is banned on penalty of death!<br /><br />Based on a true story, it is a testament to the risks one will take for the life-giving force of free thought, and discovery , in an environment of the spiritual death of Maoist dictatorship.<br />Ultimately how totalitarian tyranny -slowly and steadily, like soil erosion, or the action of the tides-an erosion and corrosion of the human spirit. It cuts man off from all nourishment, from his metaphysical roots, from religious experience, from any feeling of in and as one with the world. It produces a dehydration of the soul , spiritual death.</span>
