<div id="review_349228776" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/349228776" />
    <a title="Isabel Alcuaz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10202228-isabel-alcuaz"><img alt="Isabel Alcuaz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1545809997p2/10202228.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/349228776?book_show_action=true">Jun 15, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Isabel Alcuaz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Isabel Alcuaz" href="/user/show/10202228-isabel-alcuaz">Isabel Alcuaz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10202228-isabel-alcuaz?shelf=2012">2012</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10202228-isabel-alcuaz?shelf=read-again-later">read-again-later</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer349228776" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6692107856233659127">Balzac and the Little Chinese Seamstress is a book about two boys who are exiled to the country during China’s Cultural Revolution in order to be ‘re-educated’. There they spend their days doing menial but often dangerous work. They soon make the acquaintance of the tailor’s daughter living in the next village. When they find a secret stash of forbidden European texts translated in the Chinese language, it is with her they share them, in the hopes of making something else out of the mountain gir</span>
  <span id="freeText6692107856233659127" style="display:none">Balzac and the Little Chinese Seamstress is a book about two boys who are exiled to the country during China’s Cultural Revolution in order to be ‘re-educated’. There they spend their days doing menial but often dangerous work. They soon make the acquaintance of the tailor’s daughter living in the next village. When they find a secret stash of forbidden European texts translated in the Chinese language, it is with her they share them, in the hopes of making something else out of the mountain girl. <br /><br />I don’t have much to say about this little book. I liked it overall, but my first thought after the last page was, “What?” I thought there would be more to the story. I get the feeling that I was taking everything the narrator said literally though, and was expecting to be given hints in the writing about when something inspiring was going to happen. I didn’t expect it to be so subtle and light so I’ll probably have to read it again at some point.<br /><br />The problem is, the things that recommended the book to me when I picked it up gave the wrong impression. These are the quotes on the back, the blurb inside the jacket and author’s biography. They promised something seriously amazing and I expected to be inspired by all the award-winning, best-selling genius coming my way. I know I wouldn’t have been as disappointed if I hadn’t been expecting so much. I would’ve just enjoyed the story for what it was: a peek at life in a very different time and place. <br /><br />One of the reviewers on Goodreads named Tracey called it a “short escape” and I agree with that. It’s a short escape to another world. Just live in the three young people’s skins for a while and be them trying to grow up and experience more, despite already having been through more than most of us have. I think if I reread this book again later with that frame of mind, I’ll enjoy it more. <br /><br />I have to check out Balzac now.<br /><br /><a href="http://girllikeashadow.tumblr.com/post/25833815566" rel="nofollow noopener">full version</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="6692107856233659127" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


